ugh the Civil War has traditionally been a major period marker in U.S. history and literature, Streeby proposes a major paradigm shift by using mass culture to show that the U.S.-Mexican War and other conflicts with Mexicans and Native Americans in the borderlands were fundamental in forming the complex nexus of race, gender, and class in the United States.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 0aAmerican fictionxHistory and criticismx19th century. 0aAmerican fictiony19th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aEthnic groups in literature. 0aImperialism in literature. 0aLiterature and societyxHistoryx19th centuryxUnited States. 0aLiterature and societyzUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 0aNativism in literature. 0aPopular literaturexHistory and criticismxUnited States. 0aPopular literaturezUnited StatesxHistory and criticism. 0aRace in literature. 0aSensationalism in literature. 0aSocial classes in literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / American / General.2bisacsh  a1800s.  aacademic.  aamerican culture.  aamerican history.  aamnesia.  aanti imperialism.  aclass issues.  aclass.  aclassism.  acultural studies.  aempire.  afactory workers.  aimperial.  aimperialism.  aplantation.  apop culture history.  apop culture.  apopular culture.  arace issues.  arace.  aracism.  aromance.  ascholarly.  aunited states history.  aus history.  aus mexican war.  awartime.  aworld history.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z978311069042240uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052093587740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520935877423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520935877/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c20